# NOC Whisperer — Cursor Rules

This project is the NOC Whisperer — a multi-agent alert correlation system.

Before writing any code:
1. Read @CONTEXT.md for architecture, data structures, agent contracts, and design decisions
2. Read @EXECUTION_PLAN.md for today's specific task and acceptance test
3. Implement exactly what the session specifies — no more, no less

Coding standards:
- Python 3.11+ with full type hints on all functions
- Dataclasses for all data structures (no dicts passed between agents)
- Every class must have a docstring
- Every public method must have a docstring
- Use mock MCP tools during development — never assume live OTel stack is running
- Handle all external API calls with try/except — return [] on failure, never crash
- Load config from yaml files — never hardcode values
- Load API keys from .env — never hardcode credentials

Testing:
- Every session ends with the acceptance test passing
- Run: python -c "from module import Class; print('OK')" as minimum smoke test
- Use in-memory SQLite (:memory:) for all incident store tests
- Always run pytest using the project venv:
  .venv/bin/python3 -m pytest tests/ -v
- Never use system python3 directly for pytest.

General rules:
- All file edits including .cursorrules must be driven
  through Cursor. Never edit files manually outside Cursor.

One file per session — do not create files not listed in the current session task.

Never suggest installing torch, transformers, peft, trl, or bitsandbytes
on the local development machine. These are GPU cluster only dependencies
defined in requirements-gpu.txt.

CONTEXT.md and EXECUTION_PLAN.md are read-only during all implementation
sessions. Never modify these files when writing code. If you find a gap
or error in either file, report it as a comment in your response only.
Only modify these files when explicitly asked with the instruction:
"Update CONTEXT.md" or "Update EXECUTION_PLAN.md".

Every session that creates a new Python module must also create
a corresponding test file in tests/test_<module_name>.py
The test file must cover:
  - Valid creation of all classes
  - Invalid inputs that should raise ValueError
  - Round-trip serialization if to_dict/from_dict exist
  - The session acceptance test converted to pytest format

